<h1>Selected GloMop Publications</h1>

<ul>
  <LI> <b>System Design Issues for Internet
       Middleware Services: Deductions from a Large Client
       Trace.</b><br>
       Steven D. Gribble and Eric A. Brewer<br>
       Proceedings of the 1997 Usenix Symposium on Internet
       Technologies and Systems (USITS 97), Monterey, California, December
       1997.
       Describes our observations of the Berkeley dialup-IP population,
       and the implications of observed behavior for Internet middleware
       services such as the Berkeley Smart Proxy system.
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~gribble/papers/sys_trace.ps.gz">
              Compressed PostScript</a>
         <li> <a href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~gribble/traces/>Information
              about the traces</a>
       </ul>

  <li> <b>Cluster-Based Scalable Network Services.</b><br>
       Armando Fox, Steven D. Gribble, Yatin Chawathe, Eric A. Brewer<BR>
       Proc. 1997 Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP-16),
       St-Malo, France, Oct. 1997. (Also available from <a
       href="http://www.cs.washington.edu/sosp16/">SOSP home page.</a>)
       Describes the scalable, highly-available cluster platform on
       which TranSend, Top Gun WingMan, and other applications have been
       built.
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="/~fox/papers/sosp16.ps.gz">Compressed
              PostScript</a> (Warning: takes up to 10 <i>minutes</i> to
              print due to embedded hi-res graphs)
         <li> <a href="/~fox/papers/sosp16.pdf">PDF</a> (one of the
              graphs is missing, since PDF Writer couldn't handle it)
         <li> You can <a href="download.html">download</a> the
              <i>TranSend</i> scalable proxy described in this paper.
       </ul>

  <li> <b>Orthogonal Extensions to the WWW User Interface Using
       Client-Side Technologies.</b>  This short paper accompanies a
       demo to presented at <a href="http://www.acm.org/uist/">UIST
       '97</a>.  Discussion of how to unobtrusively present the UI for a
       "web intermediation" service.<br>
       Armando Fox, Steven D. Gribble, Yatin Chawathe, Anthony
       S. Polito, Andrew C. Huang, Benjamin Ling, Eric A. Brewer<br>
       Proc. 10th Annual Symposium on User Interface Software and
       Technology (UIST 97), October 1997, Banff, Canada.
       <ul>
         <li> Abstract (<a href="/~fox/papers/UIST97.pdf">PDF</a>)
         <li> Abstract (<a href="/~fox/papers/UIST97.ps.gz">Compressed
              PostScript</a>) 
       </ul>

  <LI><B>Adapting to Network and Client Variability via On-Demand Dynamic
       Distillation <BR>
       </B>Armando Fox, Steven D. Gribble, Eric A. Brewer, Elan Amir <BR>
       Proc. Seventh Intl. Conf. on Arch. Support for Prog. Lang. and
       Oper. Sys. (ASPLOS-VII), Oct. 1996, Cambridge, MA.  Various
       specific examples, with performance numbers, of why
       datatype-specific distillation is useful for overcoming
       network and client limitations.
       <UL>
         <LI>Paper (<A
              HREF="/~fox/papers/adaptive.ps.gz">PostScript</A>,
              <A HREF="/~fox/papers/adaptive.pdf">PDF</A>)
              
         <LI>Slides (<A href="/~fox/papers/ASPLOS7_slides/index.htm">HTML</A>)
              
         <LI>Slides (PDF)
       </UL>
       
       <a name="charon">
  <LI><B>Security On the Move:&nbsp;Indirect Authentication Using Kerberos
       <br>
       </B>Armando Fox and Steven D. Gribble <BR>
       Proc. Second ACM&nbsp;Conf. on Mobile Computing (MobiCom 96),
       Nov. 1996, White Plains, NY.  Lightweight Kerberos-based security
       for small devices, by proxying the Kerberos handshake in a way
       that delegates a subset of the user's trust to the proxy and
       results in minimal, well-defined compromise scenarios even if the
       proxy is subverted.  An implementation on the (now defunct) Sony
       MagicLink PDA is also described.
       <UL>
         <LI>Paper (PDF)
         <li> You can also <a href="download.html">download the software</a>
       </ul>

  <LI><B>Reducing WWW Latency and Bandwidth Requirements via Real-Time
       Distillation<BR>
       </B><A HREF="http://WWW.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox">Armando Fox</A> and <A HREF="http://WWW.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~brewer">Eric
       A. Brewer <BR>
       </A>Proc. Fifth International World Wide Web Conference, May 1996, Paris,
       France.  Describes <I>Pythia</I>, an early prototype of a Web
       proxy supporting image distillation and refinement.
       
       <UL>
         <LI>Paper <a href="http://www5conf.inria.fr/fich_html/papers/P48/Overview.html">(HTML)</a>
              
         <LI>Slides <a href="http://www5conf.inria.fr/fich_html/slides/papers/PS16/P48/overview.htm">(HTML)</a>
         <li> <a href="download.html">Download Pythia</a>
       </UL>

  <LI><B>The Bay Area Research Wireless Access Network(BARWAN)<BR>
       </B>Randy H. Katz, Eric A. Brewer, Elan Amir, Hari Balakrishnan,
       Armando Fox, Steve Gribble, Todd Hodes, Daniel Jiang, Giao Thanh
       Nguyen, Venkata Padmanabhan, Mark Stemm. <BR>
       Proceedings Spring COMPCON Conference 1996.  Overview of the
       wireless and mobile computing architecture that formed the
       original motivation for adaptation via distillation and refinement.
       <UL>
         <LI>Paper (compressed PostScript)
       </UL>

</ul>

<hr>

<h1>Non-Refereed Work and Internal Skunkworks</h1>

<ul>
  <li><A HREF="http://www.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~gribble/magiccap/magiccap.html">
       Proxied MIME Email Reader for Sony MagicLink</A><br><br>

       >An MH-compatible email client that exploits distillation for retrieving
       MIME included images. Interestingly, the performance bottleneck is GIF
       decoding time on the MagicLink.
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~gribble/cs294-3_multimedia/project/project.html">Real-Time
       Streams to PDA's</A><br><br>
       Why it's hard to do (the CPU is <I>not</I> necessarily the bottleneck!),
       and some suggestions for PDA hardware and software makers that will make
       it less painful in the future. 
  <li> <A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/cs294-3">GloMap: Distillation
       on a Geographic Database</A><br><BR>
       An application of datatype-specific distillation, where map data
       is the datatype of interest.  A graphical interface
       allows the user to zoom in and out on map data retrieved from a
       multi-gigabyte map database stored on an Illustra SQL
       server. Zooming out decimates the quality of the outline
       representation; zooming in (refinement) trades area for
       resolution. Unfortunately the demo can no longer be run, because
       I no longer have access to the SQL data. But if you are
       interested in seeing this and want to pursue it as a long-term
       project, I can try to get access again.
</ul>

